WEBVTT

00:00:00.031 --> 00:00:04.158
SPEAKER_00: By January 1986, the space shuttle had flown 24 times.

00:00:05.120 --> 00:00:06.883
SPEAKER_00: Each flight reinforced one idea.

00:00:06.923 --> 00:00:08.365
SPEAKER_00: The system worked.

00:00:09.367 --> 00:00:12.712
SPEAKER_00: Across those flights, engineers documented O-ring damage.

00:00:13.493 --> 00:00:17.922
SPEAKER_00: Erosion, blow-by, hot gas past seals designed to hold.

00:00:18.763 --> 00:00:21.448
SPEAKER_00: Low-temperature flights all showed distress.

00:00:21.428 --> 00:00:25.074
SPEAKER_00: But each flight survived, and the warning lost force.

00:00:26.155 --> 00:00:27.739
SPEAKER_00: Danger became a known condition.

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:30.382
SPEAKER_00: A stop signal became a line item.

00:00:31.425 --> 00:00:34.951
SPEAKER_00: The night before Challenger, engineers recommended against launch.

00:00:35.953 --> 00:00:36.975
SPEAKER_00: The burden shifted.

00:00:37.034 --> 00:00:42.423
SPEAKER_00: Instead of proving it safe to fly, they were asked to prove it was unsafe.

00:00:43.417 --> 00:00:49.088
SPEAKER_00: On the coldest morning the program had ever faced, 73 seconds was all the physics needed.

00:00:49.149 --> 00:00:51.353
SPEAKER_00: The warning was never missing.

00:00:52.295 --> 00:00:54.159
SPEAKER_00: It had been made survivable for too long.

00:00:54.942 --> 00:00:57.527
SPEAKER_00: Small causes, massive consequences.
